  "text": "Activity in the tibialis anterior muscle was measured using surface electromyography (EMG), as can be seen in Figure 1 .A. Initially the skin was lightly abraded, and then two surface electrodes (30 x 22 mm, type Neuroline 720, Ambu A/S, Denmark) were placed along the muscle fiber direction over the muscle with an inter-electrode distance of 20 mm. The signal was amplified (up to 20000 times) and filtered (5-500 Hz, 2nd order) by custom-made EMG amplifiers (Aalborg University, Denmark). Afterwards, it was sampled (2000 Hz) and stored (1000 ms window including 200 ms of pre-stimulation activity, commonly used to verify that there is no muscle activity before the stimulation), using a software specifically developed for NWR acquisition and analysis [CITATION_1] . The NWR was quantified within the 60-180 ms post-stimulation interval (Figure 1 .B).",
